{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180922193345|860747761","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Tom_MacArthur","to":"Tom MacArthur"}],"pages":{"42756935":{"pageid":42756935,"ns":0,"title":"Tom MacArthur","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-22T19:34:18Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{for|other persons with similar names|Thomas McArthur (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Tom MacArthur\n|image       = Tom MacArthur official photo.jpg\n|state       = [[New Jersey]]\n|district    = {{ushr|NJ|3|3rd}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2015\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[Jon Runyan]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_name  = Thomas Charles MacArthur\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1960|10|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Hebron, Connecticut]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education   = [[Hofstra University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n|website     = {{url|macarthur.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Thomas Charles MacArthur''' (born October 16, 1960) is an American former insurance executive and politician.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://whyy.org/articles/n-j-gop-rep-tom-macarthur-dem-challenger-andy-kim-face-off-in-forum/|title=N.J. GOP Rep. Tom MacArthur, Dem challenger Andy Kim face off in forum|work=WHYY|access-date=2018-09-10|language=en-US}}</ref> He is the member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] for {{ushr|NJ|3}}. A [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], MacArthur served on the [[city council]] of [[Randolph, New Jersey]], from 2011 through 2013, and as its mayor in 2013. He was elected to the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/04/us_rep_macarthur_tries_to_break_on_through_to_the.html#incart_2box_nj-homepage-featured|title=N.J.'s rookie Republican learns: Even in divided D.C., he's got to deal with Dems|work=NJ.com|accessdate=May 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and career==\nMacArthur grew up in [[Hebron, Connecticut]]. He received his [[bachelor's degree]] from [[Hofstra University]].<ref name=app>{{cite news|url=http://www.app.com/story/news/politics/new-jersey/2014/05/03/a-look-at-congressional-candidate-tom-macarthur/2130838/|title=A look at congressional candidate Tom MacArthur|date=May 3, 2014|agency=Associated Press |accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref> After graduating from Hofstra, MacArthur became an insurance adjuster.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/330332-meet-the-centrist-trying-to-strike-a-deal-on-healthcare|title=Meet the centrist trying to strike a deal on healthcare|author=Marcos, Christina|work=The Hill|date=April 25, 2017|access-date=May 16, 2018}}</ref> He served as the chairman and CEO of York Risk Services Group, a multi-national organization that helps people manage insurance claims. He was chairman and [[chief executive officer]] of York Risk Services Group for 11 years. He served on the [[Randolph, New Jersey]], [[City council|Township Council]] from 2011 through 2013, including a tenure as mayor in 2013.<ref name=app/>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Tom MacArthur official congressional photo.jpg|thumb|MacArthur's freshman portrait]]\n\n===2014 election===\nWhen [[Jon Runyan]], a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] who represented {{ushr|NJ|3}} in the [[United States House of Representatives]], announced that he would not run for reelection in 2014, MacArthur chose to run for the Republican Party nomination. MacArthur resigned from the Randolph council to move into the congressional district.<ref>Knapp, Claire. [http://newjerseyhills.com/randolph_reporter/news/former-fire-chief-is-new-randolph-councilman-forstenhausler-will-fill/article_7528d66c-9284-11e3-8d8c-0019bb2963f4.html \"Former fire chief is new Randolph Councilman; Forstenhausler will fill MacArthur's term\"], ''Randolph Reporter'', February 10, 2014; accessed July 6, 2014; \"Mark Forstenhausler, 54, was sworn in as a member of the Township Council on Thursday, Feb. 6, to complete the term vacated by Tom MacArthur.\"</ref> He ran against [[Steve Lonegan]] in the Republican Party's [[primary election]], and defeated him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/2014-06-05/news/50333132_1_steve-lonegan-republican-party-third-district|title=MacArthur, Belgard to compete for N.J.'s Third District seat |work=Philly.com |date=June 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMacArthur faced [[Aimee Belgard]] of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] in the general election. MacArthur's campaign expenditures totaled $5.6 million, with MacArthur personally contributing over $5 million to his campaign from his personal fortune.<ref name=\"OpenSecrets\">{{cite web |url=https://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00036155&newmem=Y|title=Rep. Thomas MacArthur, Cycle Fundraising, 2013-14|publisher=Center for Responsive Politics |work=OpenSecrets.org|accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/04/most_expensive_open_seat_house_race_in_2014_was_wa.html|title=N.J. scrap was nation's most expensive for open U.S. House seat in 2014|publisher=NJ.com|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref> MacArthur outspent Belgard by about three to one (with both campaign's spending equaling a combined total of $7.4 million), causing the race to be the most expensive 2014 open-seat contest in the country.<ref name=\"OpenSecrets2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/races/election.php?state=NJ&cycle=2014|title=New Jersey Congressional Races in 2014|publisher=Center for Responsive Politics|work=OpenSecrets.org|accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nMacArthur defeated Belgard by nearly a 10-point margin, decisively winning the popular vote in [[Ocean County, New Jersey|Ocean County]], and coming in a very close second in [[Burlington County, New Jersey|Burlington County]], losing that part of the district by only 352 votes.<ref name=\"general2014\"/>\n\nMacArthur was sworn in on January 6, 2015, along with 58 other new members of the House of Representatives.<ref name=\"ABC-114\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/114th-congress-opening-day-republicans-reins-capitol-hill/story?id=28013714|title=Home > Politics 114th Congress' Opening Day: Republicans Take the Reins on Capitol Hill|date=January 6, 2015|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=May 15, 2015|author=Dooley, Erin|author2=Saenz, Arlette|author3=Parkinson, John}}</ref> He was assigned to the [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Armed Services Committee]] and two of its subcommittees, the [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]] and [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel|Subcommittee on Military Personnel]]. MacArthur was elected Vice Chairman of the latter subcommittee. He was also assigned to the [[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Natural Resources Committee]] as well as two of its subcommittees, the [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Federal Lands|Subcommittee on Federal Lands]] and the [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Water, Power and Oceans|Subcommittee on Water, Power, and Oceans]].<ref name=\"house-gov\">{{cite web|url=https://macarthur.house.gov/about/full-biography|title=Congressman Tom MacArthur, 3rd District of New Jersey, Committees and Caucuses |date=2015|publisher=House of Representatives|accessdate=May 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn February 2, 2015, MacArthur introduced the \"Disaster Assistance Fairness and Accountability Act of 2015\"<ref name=\"Congress1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/638?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22disaster+assistance+fairness+and+accountability%22%5D%7D|title=H.R. 638 \u2013 Disaster Assistance Fairness and Accountability Act of 2015 |work=Congress.gov|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> that will prevent the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] from taking back disaster relief funds from individuals who applied for them in good faith.<ref name=\"Zimmer1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.app.com/story/news/local/sandy-two-years-later/2015/02/03/macarthur-sandy-fema/22816909/|title=Another proposal to stop FEMA's Sandy aid clawbacks|date=February 3, 2015|author=Zimmer, Russ|newspaper=Asbury Park Press|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref> On March 25, 2015, MacArthur introduced the \"Veterans' Mental Health Care Access Act\"<ref name=\"Congress2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/1604?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22disaster+assistance+fairness+and+accountability%22%5D%7D|title=H.R. 1604 \u2013 Veterans' Mental Health Care Access Act|work=Congress.gov|accessdate=May 6, 2015}}</ref> to allow veterans with a Choice Card to access mental health care at any facility eligible for reimbursement by the [[Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services]].<ref name=\"Joyce\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsworks.org/index.php/local/item/81106-congressman-macarthur-pushing-to-expand-mental-health-service-options-for-veterans|title=Congressman MacArthur pushing to expand mental health service options for veterans|date=April 24, 2015|author=Joyce, Tom |newspaper=Newsworks |accessdate=April 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BCT1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.burlingtoncountytimes.com/news/local/macarthur-veterans-need-better-access-to-mental-health-care-services/article_7496e6ef-0295-5863-9dee-a000bfdfcbca.html |title=MacArthur: Veterans need better access to mental health care services|date=April 26, 2015|author=Levinsky, David|newspaper=Burlington County Times|access-date=May 6, 2015}}</ref> Both bills were considered \"dead,\" by virtue of a failure to garner approval from Republican-led subcommittees, before the final [[Adjournment sine die|''sine die'' Adjournment of the 114th Congress.]]<ref name=\"H.R.1604-Actions\">{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/1604/all-actions|title=All Actions H.R.1604 \u2014 114th Congress (2015-2016)|date=April 7, 2015 |publisher=Library of Congress |work=Congress.gov |accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"H.R.638-Actions\">{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/house-bill/638/all-actions|title=All Actions H.R.638 \u2014 114th Congress (2015-2016)|date=February 5, 2015|publisher=Library of Congress|work=Congress.gov|accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://legiscan.com/US/research/HB638/2015|title=Legislative Research: US HB638 &#124; 2015-2016 &#124; 114th Congress|publisher=LegiScan|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Tom MacArthur|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr1604|title=Veterans\u2019 Mental Health Care Access Act (2015; 114th Congress H.R. 1604) |publisher=GovTrack.us|date=March 25, 2015|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Tom MacArthur|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/114/hr638|title=Disaster Assistance Fairness and Accountability Act of 2015 (2015; 114th Congress H.R. 638)|publisher=GovTrack.us|date=February 2, 2015|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2016 election===\nMacArthur ran for re-election in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Levinsky|first1=David|title=Tom MacArthur kicks off congressional re-election campaign |url=http://www.burlingtoncountytimes.com/news/local/election/tom-macarthur-kicks-off-congressional-re-election-campaign/article_d189c3a4-f78a-11e5-9fc8-5f69c56633a8.html |accessdate=April 29, 2016|publisher=Burlington County Times|date=March 31, 2016}}</ref> He ran unopposed in the Republican primary. In the general election, he faced Democrat Frederick John Lavergne.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hefler|first1=Jan|title=Frederick LaVergne to face Rep. Tom MacArthur in fall |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/20160608_Frederick_LaVergne_to_face_Rep__Tom_MacArthur_in_fall.html|accessdate=June 8, 2016|publisher=Philly.com|date=June 8, 2016}}</ref> MacArthur won the election with 60% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Melisurgo|first1=Len|title=Live congressional election results, ballot questions in N.J. |url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2016/11/live_results_nj_congressional_elections_2016.html|accessdate=November 11, 2016|publisher=NJ.com|date=November 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt his second term MacArthur was appointed to the Committee on Financial Services and stepped down from the Armed Services Committee and the Natural Resources Committee.<ref>{{cite news|title=MacArthur moving from Armed Services Committee to Financial Services|url=http://www.burlingtoncountytimes.com/news/local/macarthur-moving-from-armed-services-committee-to-financial-services/article_85f169bc-d36f-11e6-898c-dbba945ea821.html|author=Levinsky, David|date=January 5, 2017|publisher=[[Burlington County Times]]access-date=September 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tom MacArthur's Biography |url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/152113/tom-macarthur#.WcJOUsh96qY|publisher=[[Vote Smart]]|access-date=September 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe is a member of the [[Republican Main Street Partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018 election===\n{{see also|United States House of Representatives elections in New Jersey, 2018#District 3}}\nMacArthur will face [[Andy Kim (politician)|Andy Kim]] in the midterm election on November 6.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Subcommittee on Housing and Insurance]]\n**[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Subcommittee on Capital Markets, Securities, and Investments]]\n\n==Political positions==\nMacArthur was ranked as the 44th most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives during the [[114th United States Congress]] (and the third most bipartisan member of the U.S. House of Representatives from New Jersey) in the [[The Lugar Center|Lugar Center]] - [[McCourt School of Public Policy]] Bipartisan Index.<ref>The Bipartisan Index ranks members of the United States Congress by their degree of bipartisanship (by measuring the frequency each member's bills attract co-sponsors from the opposite party and each member's co-sponsorship of bills by members of the opposite party). {{Cite web|title=Our Work: Bipartisan Index|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/ourwork-Bipartisan-Index.html|publisher=[[The Lugar Center]]|access-date=September 20, 2017}} \n {{Citation|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/The%20Lugar%20Center%20-%20McCourt%20School%20Bipartisan%20Index%20114th%20Congress%20House%20Scores.pdf|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|publisher=[[The Lugar Center]] |date=March 7, 2016|accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, [[Project Vote Smart|Vote Smart]], a non-profit, non-partisan research organization that collects and distributes information on candidates for public office in the United States, \"researched presidential and congressional candidates' public records to determine candidates' likely responses on certain key issues.\" According to Vote Smart's 2016 analysis, MacArthur generally supports pro-life legislation, opposes an income tax increase, opposes mandatory minimum sentences for non-violent drug offenders, opposes federal spending and supports lowering taxes as a means of promoting economic growth, opposes requiring states to adopt federal education standards, supports the building of the [[Keystone Pipeline]], supports government funding for the development of renewable energy, opposes the federal regulation of greenhouse gas emissions, opposes gun-control legislation, supports repealing the [[Affordable Care Act]], supports requiring immigrants who are unlawfully present to return to their country of origin before they are eligible for citizenship, opposes same-sex marriage, supports increased American intervention in [[Iraq]] and [[Syria]] beyond air support, and opposes allowing individuals to divert a portion of their [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] taxes into personal retirement accounts.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|title=Tom McArthur's Issue Positions (Political Courage Test)|url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/152113/tom-macarthur/#.WlacbktG0js|publisher=[[Vote Smart]]|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs of January 2018, MacArthur had voted with his party in 88.5% of votes in the [[115th United States Congress]] and voted in line with President Trump's position in 93.2% of the votes.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://projects.propublica.org/represent/members/M001193-thomas-macarthur|title=Represent|last=Willis|first=Derek|work=ProPublica|access-date=March 3, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/congress-trump-score/thomas-macarthur/|title=Tracking Thomas MacArthur In The Age Of Trump|last=Bycoffe|first=Aaron|date=January 30, 2017|work=FiveThirtyEight|accessdate=March 3, 2017}}</ref> It's been noted that he votes with Trump more consistently than any other federal lawmaker from New Jersey.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/08/this_pro-trump_congressman_could_be_in_real_troubl.html|title=This pro-Trump Jersey congressman could be in real trouble. Here's why.|work=NJ.com|access-date=2018-09-09|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Economy and taxes ===\nMacArthur was the only member of Congress from the New Jersey congressional delegation to vote yes for the federal [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]]; other lawmakers harshly criticized the adverse impact of the bill on New Jersey taxpayers.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=http://observer.com/2017/11/macarthur-votes-for-gop-tax-overhaul/|title=MacArthur Votes for GOP Tax Overhaul|date=2017-11-17|work=Observer|access-date=2018-09-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2017/12/04/the-gops-10000-cap-on-property-tax-deductions-and-how-it-affects-one-congressional-district/|title=Analysis {{!}} The GOP\u2019s $10,000 cap on property tax deductions and how it affects one congressional district|last=Kessler|first=Glenn|date=December 4, 2017|work=Washington Post|access-date=December 8, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/11/macarthurs_high_risk_game_poses_risks_and_rewards.html|title=Why this N.J. Republican keeps voting for things that could hurt Jersey|work=NJ.com|access-date=2018-09-10|language=en-US}}</ref> The tax plan would lead to an aggregate tax cut in most states, but has stirred controversy in New Jersey due to the decrease in the State and Local Tax (SALT) deduction to $10,000, which means that the bill raises taxes on many New Jersey citizens.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> MacArthur explained his vote by asserting that \"nearly all taxpayers\" in his district do not need SALT deductions above $10,000.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> When asked to elaborate by the ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' fact-checker, MacArthur said that 93% of his constituents did not pay SALT higher than $10,000 and shared his team's calculations with the ''Washington Post''.<ref name=\":6\" /> The ''Washington Post'' fact-checker gave MacArthur \"Two Pinocchios\", writing that \"even that accounting ignores the interaction of the property tax provision with other parts of the tax bill, so even people who would benefit from the cap still might find themselves with an increase in taxes. MacArthur appears to have worked diligently to tilt the bill so that it would benefit his constituents, but he oversells his achievement.\"<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nMacArthur was the only member of the New Jersey congressional delegation to vote in favor of a bill that funded farm subsidies for five additional years while imposing new restrictions on food stamp usage.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/05/only_1_nj_rep_backed_trump_and_voted_for_farm_bill.html|title=This Republican was only Jersey politico to back bill that would have cut N.J. food stamps|work=NJ.com|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> According to [[NJ.com]], the bill, which did not pass, would have cost 35,000 New Jersey residents their access to food stamps.<ref name=\":4\" /> According to [[Vote Smart|Vote Smart's]] 2016 analysis, MacArthur generally opposes allowing individuals to divert a portion of their [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] taxes into personal retirement accounts.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Education ===\nAccording to [[Vote Smart|Vote Smart's]] 2016 analysis, MacArthur generally opposes requiring states to adopt federal education standards.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Environment ===\nThe League of Conservation Voters has given him a lifetime score of 10%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://scorecard.lcv.org/moc/tom-macarthur|title=Check out Representative Tom MacArthur's Environmental Voting Record|work=League of Conservation Voters Scorecard|access-date=March 3, 2017}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=January 2018}} MacArthur opposes the Trump administration's proposal to open New Jersey's waters to offshore oil and gas drilling.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.app.com/story/news/local/monmouth-county/land-environment/2018/01/06/atlantic-oil-drilling-phil-murphy-lawmakers-nj/1007443001/|title=Atlantic oil drilling: Phil Murphy, lawmakers don't want it off NJ|work=Asbury Park Press|access-date=January 9, 2018}}</ref> According to [[Vote Smart|Vote Smart's]] 2016 analysis, MacArthur generally supports the building of the [[Keystone Pipeline]], supports government funding for the development of renewable energy, and opposes the federal regulation of greenhouse gas emissions.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Gun control ===\nAccording to [[Vote Smart|Vote Smart's]] 2016 analysis, MacArthur generally opposes gun-control legislation.<ref name=\":7\" /> He has described himself as a a supporter of the [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]] and has a 93% rating from the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2018/02/post_104.html|title=N.J. Republican just did a big switch on guns after Florida shooting|work=NJ.com|access-date=2018-09-10|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nj.com/opinion/index.ssf/2018/03/nj_congressmans_gun_record_doesnt_match_his_rhetor.html|title=On guns, N.J. Congressman's rhetoric doesn't match his horrid record {{!}} Editorial|work=NJ.com|access-date=2018-09-10|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\nMacArthur has repeatedly called for repealing the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] and helped craft legislation for its repeal.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/152113/tom-macarthur/#.WLi16xKLSfQ|title=The Voter's Self Defense System |website=Project Vote Smart|language=en-US|access-date=March 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nj.com/opinion/index.ssf/2018/04/macarthur_trump.html|title=Tom MacArthur is trying to fool you. He's a partisan warrior. {{!}} Moran|work=NJ.com|access-date=2018-09-09|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.northjersey.com/story/news/new-jersey/2018/08/14/2018-midterms-macarthur-and-kim-virtually-tied-nj-battleground/976457002/|title=Midterm election poll: Tom MacArthur, Andy Kim are in a virtual tie|work=North Jersey|access-date=2018-09-10|language=en}}</ref> However, in January 2017, he was one of nine Republicans who voted no on its repeal.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.northjersey.com/story/news/politics/2017/01/13/nj-congressman-macarthur-votes-no-repeal-obamacare/96560146/|title=N.J. GOP Congressman MacArthur votes no on Obamacare repeal|work=North Jersey|access-date=March 3, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":3\"/>\n\nOn March 20, 2017, MacArthur announced his support for the [[American Health Care Act of 2017]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/C7aaWftX4AA3O6J.jpg |format=JPG |title=McSally, McClintock, MacArthur & Aderholt Welcome Changes to AHCA |website=Pbs.twimg.com |accessdate=May 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 25, 2017, MacArthur introduced an amendment to the Act which became known as the MacArthur Amendment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/10/us/politics/election-american-health-care-act-tom-macarthur.html|title=In New Jersey, Democrats Hope No Good Health Care Compromise Goes Unpunished|access-date=2018-09-10|language=en}}</ref> It permits states to waive out of Obamacare\u2019s ban on pre-existing conditions, allowing insurers to charge sick people higher premiums than healthy people. It also dictates that health insurance offered to members of Congress and their staffs not be included in the exemption from covering pre-existing conditions.<ref>Kliff, Sarah. [https://www.vox.com/2017/4/25/15429982/gop-exemption-ahca-amendment \"Republicans exempt their own insurance from their latest health care proposal\"], \"Vox\", April 25, 2017, Retrieved April 26, 2017</ref> A ''Washington Post''-ABC News poll conducted in April 2017, found that 70 per cent of Americans favored protections for pre-existing conditions.<ref>Kliff, Sarah. [https://www.vox.com/2017/4/25/15422478/gop-ahca-amendment \"Republicans\u2019 new health amendment lets insurers charge sick people more, cover less\"], \"Vox\", April 25, 2017. Retrieved April 26, 2017</ref>\n\nIn response to MacArthur's vote to pass the AHCA, which would partially repeal and replace Obamacare, there were protests in his district, and MacArthur held town halls where some constituents questioned MacArthur about his vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/05/tom-macarthur-republican-town-hall-health-care/526338/|title=A Republican Congressman Meets His Angry Constituency|last=Berman|first=Russell|work=The Atlantic|access-date=December 2, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/05/10/politics/tom-macarthur-town-hall/index.html|title=MacArthur defends his linchpin health care amendment to raucous crowd|last=Fox|first=Lauren|work=CNN|access-date=2018-09-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/tom-macarthur-feels-heat-at-home-over-health-care-russia|title=Tom MacArthur Feels Heat at Home Over Health Care, Russia|last=Path\u00e9|first=Simone|last2=Path\u00e9|first2=Simone|date=2017-05-11|website=Roll Call|language=en|access-date=2018-09-10}}</ref>\n\nMacArthur resigned as chair of the [[Tuesday Group]] in May 2017 due to disagreements among its members over the AHCA.<ref>http://www.politico.com/states/new-jersey/story/2017/05/23/macarthur-resigns-as-co-chair-of-tuesday-group-112255</ref>\n\n=== LGBT ===\nAccording to [[Vote Smart|Vote Smart's]] 2016 analysis, MacArthur generally opposes same-sex marriage.<ref name=\":7\" /> He has stated that he believes marriage should only be between a man and a woman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/hoh/lgbt-staff-association-republican-board-first-time-years|title=LGBT Staff Association Has Republican on Board for First Time in Decade|last=Gangitano|first=Alex|date=2018-03-05|work=Roll Call|access-date=2018-09-10|last2=Gangitano|first2=Alex|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMacArthur lives in [[Toms River, New Jersey]], and also owns homes in Randolph and [[Barnegat Light, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"asbury pp 2014\">{{cite news |url=https://www.app.com/story/news/2014/11/04/macarthur-wins-nj-house/18501271/|title=MacArthur wins vs. Belgard in 3rd Congressional District|work=Asbury Park Press|date=November 4, 2014|agency=USA Today Network|accessdate=May 16, 2018|author=|location=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.burlingtoncountytimes.com/7db7592c-b2cc-11e7-956c-10604b9f7e7c.html|title=Big bucks flowing to Tom MacArthur, Andy Kim in 3rd District race|work=Burlington County Times|date=October 17, 2017 |agency=GateHouse Media|accessdate=May 16, 2018|author=|location=}}</ref> He is married to his wife of over 35 years, Debbie, and has two children, a son and daughter, both of whom are adopted.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/02/nj_rep_macarthur_tries_to_stay_focused_on_the_peop.html|title=N.J.'s rookie Republican: Rep. Tom MacArthur focuses on the folks back home|author=Salant, Jonathan D. |date=February 11, 2015|publisher=NJ.com|access-date=September 20, 2017}}</ref> Their first child, Gracie, was born with special needs and died in 1996 at the age of 11.<ref name=app/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://newjerseyhills.com/randolph_reporter/news/macarthur-leaving-randolph-set-to-pursue-seat-in-congress/article_ef8658da-6412-11e3-870d-0019bb2963f4.html|title=MacArthur leaving Randolph; Set to pursue seat in Congress|work=New Jersey Hills Media Group|accessdate=November 5, 2014}}</ref> In Gracie's memory, the MacArthurs founded In God's Hands Charitable Foundation, which funds programs that help wounded veterans and children affected by AIDS in Africa.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Members Guide 2015|url=http://thehill.com/new-members-guide-2014/223734-rep-elect-tom-macarthur-r-nj-03|accessdate=May 16, 2018|publisher=The Hill}}</ref>\n\nMacArthur is the wealthiest member of New Jersey's congressional delegation, with reported assets worth about $31.8 million as of July 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nj.com/politics/index.ssf/2017/07/who_is_njs_richest_member_of_congress.html|title=Who is N.J.'s richest member of Congress? The poorest? They're all ranked here|author=Salant, Jonathan D.|work=NJ.com|date=July 11, 2017|access-date=September 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change|title=Randolph Town Council election results, 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/news/local/index.ssf/2010/11/morris_county_general_election.html|title=Morris County general election results 2010|publisher=NJ.com|date=November 2, 2010|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Tom MacArthur\n  |votes      = 4,650\n  |percentage = 22.38\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = James Loveys\n  |votes      = 4,612\n  |percentage = 22.20\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Michael Guadagno\n  |votes      = 4,522\n  |percentage = 21.76\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Allen Napoliello\n  |votes      = 4,317\n  |percentage = 20.78\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change|\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Nancie Ludwig\n  |votes      = 2,672\n  |percentage = 12.86\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{